<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="46">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239656" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Camponotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Camponotus crispulus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crispulus">Camponotus crispulus</taxonomicName>
is locally sympatric in Paraguay with at least two other species in the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:26268" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Camponotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Camponotus blandus (Smith)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="blandus">C. blandus</taxonomicName>
complex, most frequently the similarly-colored 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239646" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Camponotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Camponotus rosariensis" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rosariensis">C. rosariensis</taxonomicName>
. Both species share a similarly dense pubsence over most of the body and a common bicoloration consisting of a red head and mesosoma and a dark gaster. However, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239656" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Camponotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Camponotus crispulus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crispulus">C. crispulus</taxonomicName>
is structurally more compact, with shorter appendages and a relatively tall propodeum. In my experience, the easiest character to separate 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239656" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Camponotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Camponotus crispulus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crispulus">C. crispulus</taxonomicName>
from other bicolored blandus-complex species is the unique pattern of pubescense on the gaster. While all species in the complex show some degree of medial convergence in the appressed setae on the gastric terga, in C. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239656" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Camponotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Camponotus crispulus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crispulus">crispulus</taxonomicName>
this convergence is extreme, starting on the first gastric tergite (= abd. tergite 3) well ahead of the posterior margin and continuing to the apex of the gaster almost as a visible line. Because of the distinct morphological separation in sympatry between 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239656" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Camponotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Camponotus crispulus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crispulus">C. crispulus</taxonomicName>
and other closely-related forms, I find unambiguous the elevation of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239656" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Camponotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Camponotus crispulus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crispulus">C. crispulus</taxonomicName>
to species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="47">
Material from Paraguay is a close match to Santschi’s types from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Córdoba">Cordoba</normalizedToken>
, although Santschi’s material is somewhat more pubescent. F. Smith’s 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:26268" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Camponotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Camponotus blandus (Smith)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="blandus">C. blandus</taxonomicName>
holotype worker (BMNH, examined- see discussion under 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:134673" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Camponotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Camponotus pellitus Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pellitus">C. pellitus</taxonomicName>
) from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Pará">Para</normalizedToken>
is clearly a different species, as that ant is more gracile than 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:239656" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Camponotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Camponotus crispulus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crispulus">C. crispulus</taxonomicName>
and lacks the distinct pubescence.
</paragraph>
